			<h2 class="HeadingB"> Fundamentals </h2>
  	</div>
		<div class=" col-md-7 item">
			<h4 class="HeadingG"> What is pol.is? </h4>
			<p class="foobar789">Pol.is is a web based tool for quickly gathering open ended feedback in response to an open ended question. Pol.is produces sentiment groups and other insights by running statistical analysis on voting patterns of participants in a 'conversation'.</p>
		</div>
		<div class=" col-md-7 item">
			<h4 class="HeadingG"> How does pol.is work?</h4>
			<p class="foobar789">An individual starts a pol.is conversation by asking an open ended question and sharing a link with a group of participants. Participants write comments in response to the question, and react to each other's comments by voting. Pol.is generates a real-time visualization showing opinion groups that have formed. By clicking on the groups, everyone can see the comments that separate that group from the rest of the participants. pol.is shows you which comments were most agreed upon, disagreed upon and divisive. By exploring, you and your participants gain insights.</p>
		</div>
		<div class=" col-md-7 item">
			<h4 class="HeadingG"> What problem does pol.is solve?</h4>
			<p class="foobar789">Asking an open ended question of 20, 200, or 2000 people using email, discussion threads or comment boards is problematic. It's time consuming to synthesize lots of open ended text and make meaning out of it. Pol.is synthesizes  open text automatically, producing majority and minority opinion groups and making it simple to tell which perspectives have broad consensus and which ones are divisive.</p>
		</div>
		<div class=" col-md-7 item">
			<h4 class="HeadingG"> What about upvoting/downvoting sites, such as Reddit, Stack Overflow and Quora? How is pol.is different than these?</h4>
			<p class="foobar789">Sites that use upvoting and downvoting fail to account for the presence of opinion groups. They work well when there is one best answer, and only the best answer matters. The model doesn't work well when there are multiple right answers (ie., with more subjective questions) based on values - and there are a lot of important questions like that.</p>
		</div>
		<div class=" col-md-7 item">
			<h4 class="HeadingG"> How many people do I need to have a successful conversation?</h4>
			<p class="foobar789">At least 10. Because pol.is depends on analyzing patterns of opinion, more participants means more opportunity for patterns to emerge. Pol.is works best when when you are trying to organize the opinions of tens, hundreds, or thousands of people.</p>
		</div>
		<div class=" col-md-7 item">
			<h4 class="HeadingG"> Can anyone join the conversation I create? Can I restrict access?</h4>
			<p class="foobar789"> Anyone with a link can join the conversation. Short links (pol.is/123abc) are easy for an audience to type or tweet, and more discoverable. Long links (e.g. pol.is/789xyzTBaymEdigAxwDSP6), are harder to type, but provide a basic level of security by being impossible to guess, even for a computer.</p>
		</div>
		<div class=" col-md-7 item">
			<h4 class="HeadingG"> Do all participants see the visualization? Why?</h4>
			<p class="foobar789">Yes - all participants are able to see the visualization and analyze the results. Discovering how you relate to others is a powerful motivation to give information about yourself.</p>
		</div> 
		<div class="col-md-8 item ">
			<h4 class="HeadingG"> How are pol.is conversations different from traditional surveys?</h4>
			<p class="foobar789">In short, pol.is handles open ended text responses (subjective / value based questions) much better than traditional surveys. Consider:</p>
			<ul class="foobar789">
				<li class="foobar789">Surveys require that time and effort be spent to create questions at the outset.</li>
				<li class="foobar789">Surveys require time, care &amp; intention to avoid bias.</li>
				<li class="foobar789">Survey software does not automatically analyze the data that comes back. For instance, let's say 50% of respondents agree with question A, and 50% with question B. Were those the same 50% or not? How do those answers relate to those given for question C? While it's possible to do advanced statistical analysis to discover these correlations, it takes expertise and time to do so.</li>
				<li class="foobar789">Respondents are limited in the expressiveness of their responses. If an open text field is included, it creates more work for survey analysts. </li>
				<li class="foobar789">Surveys are generally boring to fill out.</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="foobar789">With pol.is, in contrast:</p>
			<ul class="foobar789">
				<li class="foobar789">There are no questions to create. Since participants create the statements others react to, a conversation is both effortless to start and authentic to the feelings and priorities of the participants.</li>
				<li class="foobar789">Sentiment groups and correlations are produced automatically.</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="foobar789">There are logistical implications to these differences: pol.is can be deployed in seconds in response to something unexpected, like a problem that comes up in the middle of a normal day.</p>
		</div>
	</div> <!-- end row -->
			

